<font color="#FF0000">SOMETHING OF VALUE LEARNED</font><br>
<tt>Wed Dec  4  0:31:12 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
<br>
Certainly the Viet vets are in the <br>
postion to appreciate the philosopher <br>
George Santayana's observation that <br>
those who do not remember history's <br>
lessons are condemned to repeat them.  <br>
But what guarantee have we that future <br>
decision makers can act wisely enough <br>
to prevent a reoccurrence of a war <br>
we'd deeply regret.  <br>
Well, in point of fact, there is no <br>
such guarantee.  The possibility is <br>
lessened by overcoming the sort of <br>
dualistic mentality which perceives <br>
enemies and threats where they don't <br>
in fact exist.  The best justification <br>
for choosing to participate in war is <br>
if one's real safety is imminently <br>
threatened.  Failing that, any such <br>
participation is of dubious moral <br>
value.  Right now, we're having to <br>
come to terms with the fallout <br>
produced by Desert Storm.  If indeed <br>
Saddam Hussein was such a grave threat <br>
to our security here at home, the <br>
Storm experience certainly didn't <br>
liquidate that threat; he survives <br>
much to our chagrin, the Kurds <br>
suffered horrendously, and thousands <br>
of returning soldiers have contracted<br>
the noxious gulf war syndrome.<br><br>

